No, you should still raise the `ValueError` but what I'm saying is that `len(pair)` may fail so you need to handle that too in order to ensure that the `ValueError` is raised vs. whatever error might be thrown when you do `len(pair)`.

An alternative for this could be:

```python
try:
    assert len(pair) == 2
except Exception:
    raise ValueError(...)

if not all(map(callable, pair)):
    raise TypeError(...)
```

@petrjasek actually forget my last message, I've misread the diff and the lookup is OK.
the provider_name is needed here for checking the environment variable, and the page is not authorised if nothing is set in environment, so that's kind of needed here.

It may still be changed later when we have some client UI, because at this time the environment variable should not be used anymore.

@tseaver I'd do this import at module level scope, but opted do it at runtime to keep this change small.

Importing it at module scope would import `system_tests.datastore` (since it is import by `system_tests.run_system_test`. The import of `system_tests.datastore` [sets][1] the `EMULATOR_DATASET` global to `None` since we haven't had a chance yet to update `os.environ`.

[1]: https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python/blob/ffe5869aa7c31bd82483e4d52adacbf83cf0fd69/system_tests/datastore.py#L36

